In Regulating Screens, André Caron and Ronald Cohen examine how governments and non-governmental organizations have been doing their part to make television and the Internet safer for children. In practical terms, they provide parents, educators, and politicians with an up-to-date inventory of the existing laws, codes, and standards in Canada, as well as information on who administers them and how they can be accessed. Given the Internet's global reach, Caron and Cohen also describe access controls in place in the United States, Australia, the United Kingdom, and the European Union. Regulating Screens offers efficient access to otherwise scattered and difficult-to-find information; it is essential reading for anyone interested in how to safeguard children against risky content, whether accessed on broadcast or virtual platforms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChildren's television programsxGovernment policyxCanada. 0aChildren's television programsxGovernment policyzCanada. 0aChildren's television programsxSafety regulationsxCanada. 0aChildren's television programsxSafety regulationszCanada. 0aDigital mediaxSocial aspects. 0aElectronic gamesxSocial aspects. 0aInternet and childrenxGovernment policyxCanada. 0aInternet and childrenxGovernment policyzCanada. 0aInternet and childrenxSafety regulationsxCanada. 0aInternet and childrenxSafety regulationszCanada. 0aInternet and children. 0aInternet and teenagers. 0aInternet governance. 0aMass media and children. 0aVideo games and children. 0aVideo gamesxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Poverty & Homelessness.2bisacsh1 aCohen, Ronald I., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aTallim, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruytert